'''Krogh model''' is a [[Scientific modelling|scientific model]] in the area [[mass transfer]] explaining concentration of [[oxygen|molecular oxygen]] through a [[Cylinder (geometry)|cylindrical]] [[Capillary action|capillary tube]] as a function of a changing position over the capillary tube's length. It was first conceptualized by [[August Krogh]] in 1919 to describe oxygen supply in living tissues, particularly the one occurring in human [[blood vessel]]s.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wei|Anderson|1995|p=176.}}</ref>  Its applicability has been extended to various academic fields, and has been successful explaining drug diffusion, water transport, and ice formation in tissues.<ref name="Biomed Experts">{{cite journal| title=Axial oxygen diffusion in the Krogh model: modifications to account for myocardial oxygen tension in isolated perfused rat hearts measured by EPR oximetry.| pmid=16594144 | doi=10.1007/0-387-26206-7_18 | volume=566| journal=Adv Exp Med Biol| pages=127-34 | last1 = Grinberg | first1 = O | last2 = Novozhilov | first2 = B | last3 = Grinberg | first3 = S | last4 = Friedman | first4 = B | last5 = Swartz | first5 = HM}}</ref>

==Mathematical modeling==
Krogh model is derived by applying [[Fick's laws of diffusion]] and the [[Conservation of mass|law of conservation of mass]] over a radial [[Interval (mathematics)|interval]] <math>Rc \le r \le Rt</math>

==Limitations==
Although Krogh model is a good approximation, it underestimates oxygen consumption<ref name="Biomed Experts" /> because the cylinder model does not include all the tissue surrounding the capillary.<ref>{{Harvnb|Truskey|Fan|Katz|2009|p=643.}}</ref>

