{{Infobox book | italic title = | name =The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent | image = | caption = | alt = | author =[[John Erskine (educator)|John Erskine]] | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country =United States (New York, Duffield) | language =English | series = | subject =philosophy | genre = | published =1915 | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource =The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent | exclude_cover = }} '''''The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent''''' is an influential essay, part of the essay collection ''The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent, and Other Essays'' published in 1915 by [[John Erskine (educator)|John Erskine]], English professor at [[Columbia University]].{{Sfn|Graff|1989|p=278}}{{Sfn|Rubin|1992|p=161}}
The essay was first read before the [[Phi Beta Kappa Society]] of [[Amherst College]], where Erskine taught before joining Columbia. {{Sfn|Erskine|1992|p=vii}} Later, it was published in quarterly magazine ''[[The Hibbert Journal]]'' in 1914. {{Sfn|Trilling|2008|p=x}}{{Sfn|Erskine|1992|p=vii}} During his tenure at Columbia from 1909 and 1937, Erskine formulated General Honors Course. In the early 1920s he started teaching a ''great books'' course at Columbia, which later founded the influential [[Great Books]] movement.<ref name=nyt/>
==History== In 1963, the essay was published in the ''[[Gateway to the Great Books]]'' - Volume 10: Philosophical Essays, a 10-volume book series published by [[Encyclopædia Britannica Inc.]] in 1963.<ref>{{cite web| title = Gateway to the Great Books |publisher=Centre for Study of Great Ideas| url = http://www.thegreatideas.org/gbgateway.html | accessdate = 2014-05-15}}</ref>
Subsequently it was also included in the book of selected essays also titled ''The Moral Obligation to Be Intelligent: Selected Essays'' (New York: Farrar, Straus & Giroux) published posthumously in 2000), edited by [[Lionel Trilling]], another Columbia faculty and literary critic, and had an introduction by critic [[Leon Wieseltier]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Night Vision by Andrew Delbanco |publisher= The New York Review of Books | url = http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2001/jan/11/night-vision/ |author=Andrew Delbanco|date= January 11, 2001|accessdate = 2014-05-15 }}</ref> Trilling was one of Erskine's students and later taught the "Great Books" course himself; he chose the essay as the lead and the title as it characterized the essence his selection. {{Sfn|Kimmage|2009|p=322}}<ref name=nyt>{{cite web |author=Richard Gilman|authorlink=Richard Gilman|title=The Foremost Authority |url=http://partners.nytimes.com/books/00/09/24/reviews/000924.24gilmant.html |date=September 24, 2000 |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=2014-05-15}}</ref>
